According to the wikipedia entry for Campo del Cielo it was found < 1576. This may be why it is recorded as NA in the year table.

The average mass of meteorites that were recorded falling, vs.those which were just found.

falling_meteorites <- meteorites %>% 
  filter(fall == "Fell")

avg_mass_falling_meteorites <- falling_meteorites %>% 
  summarise(avg_mass = mean(mass, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  pull()

avg_mass_falling_meteorites/1000
## [1] 69.50995

Almost 70kg

How does this compare with meteorites that were just found?

## [1] 134.3877

Almost 180kg

The average mass of meteorites that are found is around two and a half that of meteorites observed while falling. This does make sense given the age of the Earth relative to the length of time that humans have existed, and also when not falling from the sky, its probably quite difficult to find a small meteorite. A long term study of found meteorites should, therefore, favour larger masses.

The trend is that over time, less meteorites are recorded per year.

What is trend in meteorites observed to have fallen in the same period?

While the number of meteorites per year has decreased over time, the number of meteorites observed falling has not, but has remained consistently low. The implication then is that we are finding old meteorites faster than new ones are falling.

The data includes lat/long co-ordinates. Plot every meteorite on a map of the world, placed where it was found.

# load in world map
earth_map <- map_data("world")

# remove the missing values from the plot
meteorites <- meteorites %>%
  filter(latitude!=0 & longitude !=0)

ggplot() +
  # continental grey background
  geom_polygon(data = earth_map, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = "grey", alpha = 1.5) +
  # plot lat/longs on top
  geom_point(data = meteorites %>% mutate(mass = mass/1000),
             aes(x = longitude, y = latitude, size = mass)) +
  coord_cartesian() +
  theme_classic() +
  theme_void() +
  labs(size = "Mass (1000kg)") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  guides(size = guide_legend(nrow = 2))

Plot only the largest (greatest mass) meteorites on the world map.

large_meteorites <- falling_meteorites %>% 
  # the selection of large meteorites will be those greater than the avg mass
  filter(mass > avg_mass_falling_meteorites) %>% 
  # change the units of mass from grams to something more sensible for the plot
  mutate(mass = mass/1000/1000)


ggplot() +
  # plot map
  geom_polygon(data = earth_map, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = "grey", alpha = 1.5) +
  # plot data
  geom_point(data = large_meteorites,
             aes(x = longitude, y = latitude, color = mass)) +
  coord_cartesian() +
  labs(color = "Mass (1000kg)", title = "Large Meteorites") +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  guides(size = guide_legend(nrow = 2))

From the plot very few meteorites exist in the largest mass category. Most are < 5*1000kg. It may be that a few very very large meteorites drag the mean average up. How does the median average of falling meteorites compare.

median_avg_mass <- falling_meteorites %>% 
  summarise(avg_mass = median(mass, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  pull()

median_avg_mass/1000
## [1] 6

6kg. It is less than 1/10th of what the mean is. The implication, then ,is that the majority of meteorites are considerably less than the mean average mass.

Plot the meteorites found falling in the last 100 years.

meteorites_last_100_years <- falling_meteorites %>% 
  filter(year > 1920) %>%
  # remove the missing values
  filter(latitude != 0 & longitude != 0)

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = earth_map, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = "grey", alpha = 1.5) +
  geom_point(data = meteorites_last_100_years,
             aes(x = longitude, y = latitude, size = mass/1000)) +
  coord_cartesian() +
  labs(title = "Meteorites observed falling since 1920", size = "Mass (1000kg)") +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",  plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  guides(size = guide_legend(nrow = 1))

Plot the meteorites observed falling in the past 40 years. Distinguish decade by colour.

recent_meteorites <- meteorites_last_100_years %>%
  filter(year >= 1980) %>% 
  mutate(decade = case_when(
    year >= 1980 & year < 1990 ~ "1980s",
    year >= 1990 & year < 2000 ~ "1990s",
    year >= 2000 & year < 2010 ~ "2000s",
    year >= 2010 & year < 2020 ~ "2010s"
  )) %>% 
  group_by(decade)

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = earth_map,
               aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = "grey", alpha = 1.5) +
  geom_point(data = recent_meteorites,
             aes(x = longitude, y = latitude,
                 colour = decade, size = mass/1000)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("1980s" = "yellow",
                                "1990s" = "orange",
                                "2000s" = "red",
                                "2010s" = "black")) +
  labs(color = "Decade",
       size = "Mass (1000kg)",
       title = "Meteorites in the last 40 years") +
  coord_cartesian() +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        legend.box.background = element_rect()) +
  guides(size = guide_legend(nrow = 2, ncol = 2),
         colour = guide_legend(nrow = 2, ncol = 2))
